 ABSTRACT 
 Gladwin, C.H., 1992. (male/female status)ed hits/effects of (material that makes plants grow better) helping payment removal programs in Malawi 
 and Cameroon. Agric. Econ., 7: 141-153. 
 Since the early 1980s, development experts and donor (services businesses/government units) have agreed on the 
 importance of (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) (change to make better/related to changing something) programs (SAPs) aimed at 'getting prices right'. 
 Adoption of changes were made (things that must exist before other things can happen) for new loans or grants in many sub-Saharan 
 African countries. In both Malawi and Cameroon, one such needed/demanded reform was government's eliminating (material that makes plants grow better) payments to the small farm part/area, (before that/before now) used to increase 
 the money-making ability of intensive farming while keeping food prices (not in a natural way/in a fake way) low. The aim of 
 this ,:&amp;gt;aper is to review (material that makes plants grow better) helping payment removal programs for their hit/effect on farmers, who 
 in sub-Saharan Africa are women. In your mind, SAP programs should benefit women producers, because much focus is placed on renewing farming-based production and matching up/making even 
 farmgate prices with world prices. But in practice, will they benefit? Are SAPs (male/female status)-neutral and affect men and women equally, or only (male/female status)-blind? 
 
 INTRODUCTION 
 
 Since the early 1980s, development experts and donor (services businesses/government units) have 
 agreed on the importance of (related to what holds something together and makes it strong) (change to make better/related to changing something) programs (SAPs) aimed 
 at 'getting prices right'. Adoption of changes - (reduction of value) of (with a too-high value assigned) 
 types of money, increases in (not in a natural way/in a fake way) low food prices and interest rates, 
 (turning things over from the government to private companies) policies, wage and hiring freezes, removal of payments, and 
 the switching of useful things/valuable supplies from the production of non-tradables to tractabies - were made (things that must exist before other things can happen) for new loans or grants in many subCorrespondence to: C. H. Gladwin, IFAS, Food and useful thing/valuable supply Money flow Department, 
 University of Florida, Gainesville, FL 32611, USA. 
 
