 Saharan African countries. In both Malawi and Cameroon, one such 
 needed/demanded reform was government's eliminating (material that makes plants grow better) payments to the 
 small farm part/area 1 , (before that/before now) used to increase the money-making ability of intensive 
 farming while keeping food prices (not in a natural way/in a fake way) low (Timmer, Falcon and 
 Pearson, p. 288). The argument was that only when total (material that makes plants grow better) use is 
 low and the ratio of (in small steps up) grain yield to (material that makes plants grow better) application is high 
 can such payments be (producing a lot for a given amount of money), relative to higher output prices or 
 greater food imports. 
 The aim of this paper is to review (material that makes plants grow better) helping payment removal programs for 
 their hit/effect on farmers, who in sub-Saharan Africa are women who 
 provide 46% of farming-based labor, on average, and produce most of the 
 food crops (Dixon, 1982). In your mind, SAP programs should benefit women 
 producers, because much focus is placed on renewing farming-based 
 production and matching up/making even farmgate prices with world prices. But in practice, 
 will they benefit? The question is: are SAPs (male/female status)-neutral (i.e., affecting 
 men and women equally), or only (male/female status)-blind (i.e., ignoring the hits/effects 
 on women and assuming them to be the same as on men)? 
 Elson (1991) claims there is a male bias in the macroeconomic thinking 
 behind SAPs because the focus on money-based groups hides a  hidden set 
 of ideas (you think are true) concerning (workers in general/hiring, training, and firing department) and their portion to production. (workers in general/hiring, training, and firing department) are treated as if they were costlessly move (from one place to another)able 
 between different activities and different crops. This ignores the sexual 
 division of labor which decides/figures out that some sorts of work are good for 
 women but no good for men, expressed in rules which require African 
 women to provision the household with food while men control export crop 
 production. This can present a (blocking thing) to SAP goals of reallocating useful things/valuable supplies - women's labor and land in Africa - from the production of 
 non-tradable survival/income crops to tradable export crops. To the extent that 
 SAPS are successful in switching useful things/valuable supplies from non-tradables to trad- 
 
 1 In Malawi, USAID (worked to reach agreement/got through) a 1985 Money-based Policy Reform Program (EPRP) with two 
 changes (helping payment removal and substitution of high analysis for low analysis (material that makes plants grow better)s) and 
 $15 million to be paid over three years (USAID, 1990). After at first cutting the 
 helping payment from 29% to 17%, in 1987/88 the government refused to cut the helping payment further, 
 claiming that transportation cost increases, the mix of hungry Mozambique runaways, 
 and falling behind maize production needed/demanded an increase in helping payment to medium-level (material that makes plants grow better) price 
 increases. USAID then cancelled the EPRP without releasing $5 million. (after that), the 
 price of (material that makes plants grow better) has increased 50%, although the helping payment has remained at 24% of delivered 
 cost. Cameroon started a (material that makes plants grow better) Subsector Removal Program (FSSRP) in 1988, when the 
 helping payment was cut from 65 to 45%, decreasing government expenses from 6 to 2.4 billion 
 (10 9 ) CFA. It was projected that the helping payment would decrease to 30% in 1989, 10% in 1990, 
 and 0 in 1991. Because it takes a while for (material that makes plants grow better) to filter down to the farmer, however, 
 (material that makes plants grow better) price increases had not yet happened in December 1989, when this study started. 
 
