 ables, women lose out as more powerful men control the (money made/good things received) that result 
 from the added (rewards or reasons for doing something) to produce tradables or export crops. 
 If this is true, then what macroeconomic policies and SAP changes 
 should be changed? In this paper, I argue against the removal of (material that makes plants grow better) 
 payments, at least for women farmers growing food crops. Section 1 shows 
 that even with (material that makes plants grow better) payments, (material that makes plants grow better) use is very low and women are 
 just starting to use it on food crops in Malawi and Cameroon. A further 
 decrease of the (material that makes plants grow better) helping payment would eliminate its use on food crops, 
 because lack of cash and (not totally pure/not totally correct) credit markets are the main restrictions 
 limiting women farmers' use of chemical (material that makes plants grow better). Section 2 explores 
 government's other options to allow women access to (material that makes plants grow better), e.g., an 
 increase in food product prices to offset the increased price of (material that makes plants grow better) 
 after helping payment removal andjor an (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of women's credit clubs; and 
 finds that women farmers, especially female headed families, are often 
 net buyers of food and too poor to want credit. Section 3 ends/decides that 
 these options, while desirable in the long run, are not substitutes for 
 making (material that makes plants grow better) cheaper now via a helping payment targeted at women. If government wants to preserve food security and encourage more (material that makes plants grow better) use on 
 food crops, then it should target (material that makes plants grow better) payments at women farmers who 
 produce food crops. 
 1. CONSTRAINTS TO FERTILIZER USE 
 
 Data on (material that makes plants grow better) use from both Malawi and Cameroon show that it is 
 very low: on average one 50-kg bag per hectare is applied. Malawi data in 
 Table 1 from 501 families show that female-headed families use 
 much less (material that makes plants grow better) (34.4 vs. 51.3 kgjha) and have smaller farm size 
 (0.8 vs. 1.33 ha) than male-headed families. Data personally collected 
 from 36 families in English speaker and Francophone Cameroon agree: 
 average (material that makes plants grow better) use is 52 kgjha, still lower on maize (30 kgjha), because 
 
