 two-thirds of the women interviewed (in the English speaker North-West 
 area of control/area of land) use no (material that makes plants grow better) at all. 
 One reason farmers apply such low levels of (material that makes plants grow better) is that they 
 increase its use until the ratio of the not important product of (material that makes plants grow better) to its 
 real price ( Pfert!Pmaize) is not 1 but greater than or equal to 2 (Timmer, 
 1974, p. 200). The ratio is usually 2 or more because farmers cannot base 
 their decisions to use or increase (material that makes plants grow better) on the judging requirement of profit 
 (biggest increase/best possible extent) alone. They also face restrictions such as lack of cash, credit, 
 knowledge of how to apply (material that makes plants grow better), and risk. Another reason comes from/is caused by 
 the nature of the sexual division of farming-based labor in the African 
 household (Gladwin and McMillan, 1989). Although portion of labor 
 rules change/differ  across areas, even within the same country, in Malawi and 
 North-West Cameroon women produce the survival/income crop maize, and 
 men produce a cash crop: tobacco and combination maize in Malawi, and coffee 
 and cocoa in Cameroon. In Malawi, women produce 'local' maize which is 
 90% of total maize production and groundnuts as a cash crop; in Cameroon, 
 women produce only the food crops of maize, yams and beans. The very 
 nature of this division of labor often leaves women without any cash with 
 which to buy (material that makes plants grow better) for survival/income maize. Either they are dependent on 
 their husbands or sons to buy (material that makes plants grow better) for them, or they must take some 
 food away from the family to sell, to buy (material that makes plants grow better) for the next season. This 
 is very hard for women to do; it is impossible in a maize-shortage household, 
 (in other words) one which regularly produces less maize than it uses/eats. The result is 
 that men buy (material that makes plants grow better) for women's maize if they have the money after 
 buying (material that makes plants grow better) for their own cash crop, and women apply little or no 
 (material that makes plants grow better) on survival/income maize. 
 Restrictions limiting (material that makes plants grow better) use 
 
 It is necessary to show a link between (not totally pure/not totally correct) credit markets and 
 women farmers' low use of (material that makes plants grow better). Multiple moving backward analysis, with 
 results shown in Table 2, shows the link between smallholders' lack of cash 
 and/or credit and their individual (material that makes plants grow better) use. The data set was from 
 Malawi's Fast (material that makes plants grow better) Survey of 1986/87, carried out as a add to/addition 
 to the Once-a-year Survey of Farming, and consisted of individual (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) data from 185 Blantyre farmers, 145 Lilongwe farmers, and 196 
 Kasungu farmers. The data set has the advantage that all fields were 
 measured by experienced technicians, and is representative of districts with 
 the biggest farmers (Lilongwe, Kasungu) and smallest farmers (Blantyre). 
 Moving backward analysis is not used here to show (things causing other things to happen), but only the 
 link between the amount of (material that makes plants grow better), CFERT (or amount per hectare, 
 CFHA) and five (things that you control (like study times), that cause other things to change (like test scores)). These include: the amount of land 
 
