 per hectare (cFHA). This is because the smaller the area helped grow, the 
 more (material that makes plants grow better) is poured on- holding other (numbers that change/things that change) (access to cashjcredit) 
 constant. The last thing just mentioned result is not a surprise when (material that makes plants grow better) comes as an 
 not dividable input of 50-kg bags to most smallholders. An different explanation for this result is that farmers try to overcome smaller (areas of owned land) 
 by using more (material that makes plants grow better), given they can overcome the NOCASH restriction. 
 Note that all (numbers that change/things that change) except (male/female status) are highly significant (P = 0.0001). 
 Then why have we included (male/female status) as an (thing that you control (like study time), that causes something else to change (like a test score))? Just to 
 show it has no direct effect on (material that makes plants grow better) use: although women household 
 heads apply completely less (material that makes plants grow better) per hectare than men heads, (male/female status) 
 does not matter when one holds constant access to credit and cash. But 
 without access to credit or cash, women household heads apply less 
 (material that makes plants grow better) than men, and get lower produces and incomes as a result (Due, 
 1991). 
 2. ALTERNATIVE POLICIES TO A FERTILIZER SUBSIDY: WILL THEY WORK 
 FOR WOMEN? 
 
 With (material that makes plants grow better) helping payment removal, there will be little or no (material that makes plants grow better) bought 
 by women farmers who are the smallest of the smallholders, because lack 
 of cash and credit are the main restrictions limiting their use of chemical 
 (material that makes plants grow better)s. Women's lack of (material that makes plants grow better) use means they cannot now strengthen 
 survival/income maize production and raise factor working well; in the future, 
 this may endanger the high level of food independence usually/(in the past) 
 enjoyed in both Malawi and Cameroon (Goheen, 1991). Government will 
 then have to import maize, the main survival/income crop, or suffer greater 
 levels of (bad food quality), and the cost of importing maize may be greater than 
 the cost of giving money to (material that makes plants grow better). 
 But, counter the helping payment removal advocates- usually found in the World 
 Bank, USAID, and Ministries of Finance - one way to offset the rising 
 price of (material that makes plants grow better) after helping payment removal is to increase producer prices of 
 food and cash crops which are kept (not in a natural way/in a fake way) low. It is true that producer 
 prices are kept (not in a natural way/in a fake way) low: in Malawi in 1986/87, maize prices had 
 been low relative to other cash crops, e.g., tobacco, cotton, groundnuts. In 
 Cameroon in 1989, farmgate prices of coffee, used by smallholders to buy 
 (material that makes plants grow better) for maize and coffee, were one-third to one-half of world coffee 
 prices. 
 Unfortunately, governments are more likely to decrease (material that makes plants grow better) payments than to increase (not in a natural way/in a fake way) low producer prices, because since colonial 
 times, paying farmers less than the world price has been the way African 
 governments tax farmers (Bates, 1981). In 1989, for example, the Cameroon 
 government was in the 2nd year of a (material that makes plants grow better) Subsector Helping payment Removal 
 
 FERTILIZER SUBSIDY REMOVAL PROGRAMS IN MALAWI AND CAMEROON 
 
 147 
 
 Program, but it also cut farmgate coffee prices in half in December, to 
 keep them at one-third the world price. So farmers were faced with a 
 double whammy: a 100% decrease in producer prices and a 50% increase 
 in the price of (material that makes plants grow better). 
 Even when government does increase producer prices, as the Malawi 
 government has done with maize prices since 1987, increasing the price of 
 maize cannot by itself substitute for keeping the price of (material that makes plants grow better) low, as 
 most smallholders do not sell maize and are in fact net buyers of maize. 
 Peters and Herrera (1988) claim that less than 15% of Malawi's smallholders are fully independent in maize production. Lele (1989, p. 16) terms the 
 structure of Malawi's farming a "(existence of two things/belief that the world consists of two opposing things)-within-(existence of two things/belief that the world consists of two opposing things)" structure, 
 within which/by which the small farm part/area is clear/separate from the large "estate" part/area and 
 smallholders are split into two groups: a minority who have a farm size 
 large enough "to produce a marketable extra and capable of taking risks 
 and a common majority experiencing spoiling or near money-based 
 (state of being unable to move)." Increasing the producer price of maize will this way be harmful 
 not only to the city-based  poor but also to the (away from cities) majority who buy maize. 
 According to Harrigan (1987), the only hope of increasing their incomes is 
 to encourage their use of (material that makes plants grow better) on survival/income (local) maize varieties, so 
 that more of their land can be taken out of survival/income and planted to cash 
 crops. Is this being done? No, 1984-1990 data show hectarage is stable in 
 local maize varieties and the supply inelastic (0.07) (USAID, 1990). For 
 farmers unable to "withdraw" into independence or an "(process of people making, selling, and buying things) of feeling of love," 
 higher food prices can hurt (Hyden and Peters, 1991). 
 (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of credit facilities: a policy other choice? 
 (in almost the same way), government's (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of credit facilities, desirable in the 
 long run, is not a good policy other choice to a (material that makes plants grow better) helping payment targeted at 
 women in the short run. Why not? To answer this question, smallholders' 
 decisions to join a credit club were modeled with separate, pre-decided 
 'decision tree models' after personal interviews with 39 farmers in Malawi 
 in 1987 (Figs. 1 and 2) and 36 farmers in Cameroon in 1989 (Fig. 3) 2 . The 
 tree model is a (not numbers-based) research method which combines in a logical 
 order the reasons - decision judging requirements ( &amp;lt; ) ) - why some farmers choose one 
 The samples personally interviewed in both countries were chosen by snowball sampling 
 and are fairly representative. In Lilongwe, Kasungu and Salima districts, Malawi, 33 of 40 
 were household heads, 26 farmers were credit club members, and 14 were not; 22 farmers 
 got credit for (material that makes plants grow better) in 1986/87, while 18 did not; 17 farmers were women household 
 heads, 20 were male heads, and three were couples interviewed together. The Cameroon 
 sample included 21 women, 14 men, and 1 couple in both English speaker (Kom area) and 
 Francophone (Dschang area) Cameroon. 
