 ple of micro-money flow/money-based studies. If the cost of buying (material that makes plants grow better) is much less than the 
 cost of getting it on credit, the farmer 'goes down' the left hand path of the 
 tree. The farmer then buys (material that makes plants grow better) if: hejshe has enough cash to buy all 
 the (material that makes plants grow better) needed (judging requirement 9) and he/she hasn't other more pressing 
 needs for the cash such as school fees, clothing, etc. (judging requirement 10); or 
 hejshe has other uses for the cash so needs the credit, but thinks there's a 
 risk of not being able to pay back the loan (judging requirement 11), and this risk of 
 non-repayment is greater than the risk of 'inviting hunger' if you grow 
 maize varieties (local or combination) without (material that makes plants grow better) (judging requirement 12). Why is not 
 repaying a credit loan so risky? Farmers in default report that club 
 members and extension agents steal their animals, oxcarts, and even the 
 doors and roofs to their houses to hold until the farmer or a family member 
 repays the loan. 
 On the other hand, the farmer 'goes down' the right hand branch of the 
 tree and gets the credit for at least some of the needed (material that makes plants grow better) if he 1she 
 thinks there is little difference in the costs of owning (material that makes plants grow better) or he j she 
 does not have all the cash needed to buy it or has other more pressing 
 needs for this cash and can also pass the risk. restrictions. The farmer will 
 take the risks of credit, (in other words), of not being able to pay back the loan, if hejshe 
 thinks "you invite hunger if you grow local maize without (material that makes plants grow better)", and 
 judges the danger of hunger to be greater than the danger of not being able 
 to pay back the loan (judging requirement 12). 
 Of what use is the model? By illustrating the thinking farmers use to 
 make this decision, the model identifies the main factors limiting credit 
 use, and for the purposes of this paper, the major restrictions limiting 
 women's credit use. In this sample, these are: lack of a credit club in the 
 village (4 women), fear of not being able to pay back the loan (3 women); and 
 being too old or poor to want credit (2 women). Half of the women in the 
 sample this way eliminate the credit option quickly, in the first stage of the 
 decision process, without (thinking about/when one thinks about) parts of cost or riskiness. I decide that there are too many restrictions on women farmers for much 
 credit (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) to be (able to be done) in the short run. Although desirable in the 
 long run, it is not a good policy substitute for a (material that makes plants grow better) helping payment targeted at 
 women in the short run. 
 
 'Credit' decision in the Cameroon 
 Cameroon farmers do not process the same decision judging requirements as do 
 Malawians, when deciding whether or not to get credit, because there are 
 practically no credit clubs in Cameroon. Of 36 farmers interviewed, 32 say 
 no to judging requirement 1, "Is there a club in your area that you can join," in the 
 information-processing model of Fig. 3. Only four farmers interviewed in 
 
 152 
 
 C.H. GLADWIN 
 
 Cameroon reported receiving MIDENO government credit; two of them 
 belonged to a MIDENO women's club. In 1989, they had received their 
 first credit for (material that makes plants grow better). 
 But there are other options called credit, supplied through the local 
 coffee cooperative (judging requirement 2, figure 3), the local credit union (judging requirement 4), 
 or the native (to) njangi or tontin systems of saving (judging requirement 5), to which 
 almost every Cameroonian belongs. Members of the local coffee cooperative sell their collected coffee in January and receive their next year's 
 (material that makes plants grow better) at the same time, to be applied in February thru April to both 
 coffee and maize (judging requirement 3). This is called 'credit' but strictly speaking, 
 this is a cash transaction, and the cooperative does not give more (material that makes plants grow better) 
 than can be paid for with last year's coffee. Members of local credit unions 
 save on a monthly basis for a year and borrow against that money during 
 the second year; but they cannot borrow more than what they have saved. 
 Members of an njangi can do the same, (in other words), build up their money to 
 borrow during the 2nd year, or put money into a common pot every month 
 to receive twelve times that amount once a year. With these sources of 
 'credit', more men get credit from the coffee cooperative (8 of a total 13), 
 and more women do not get credit (11 of a total 14). This is because 
 women in some areas (the Northwest) are not allowed to raise coffee for 
 sale, and so do not have a cash crop to save up enough njangi money to 
 cover a (material that makes plants grow better) loan. 
 3. CONCLUSION 
 
 Policy options are limited for African governments trying to juggle SAP 
 needed things with women farmers' demands for low-priced (material that makes plants grow better) as a 
 way to strengthen food production. This paper has shown that policy options 
 that work for men farmers - an increase in producer prices, an (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) 
 of credit - do not often work for women farmers, because they tend to be 
 net buyers of food who suffer when food prices rise, producers of survival/income and not cash crops, and too poor to want credit. To the extent that 
 SAPs are successful in switching more useful things/valuable supplies from non-tradables to 
 tradables, women will be unable to get access to (material that makes plants grow better) to grow their 
 non-tradable crops more intensively. Is there a solution to this two-headed problem? 
 One solution is to target (material that makes plants grow better) payments at women farmers for food 
 production. This can be done via women's credit clubs, like those of 
 MIDENO in Cameroon and the Women's Programme in Malawi. Government can strengthen each women's club's 'revolving credit fund', used to 
 bail out individual defaulting members, by giving the club a small amount 
 when a club member supervises the use of paid-for (material that makes plants grow better) on 
 another's farm. Credit clubs can this way serve not only to expand credit but 
 
 FERTILIZER SUBSIDY REMOVAL PROGRAMS IN MALAWI AND CAMEROON 
 
 153 
 
 also to supervise the proper use of paid-for (material that makes plants grow better) bought with cash. 
 Will there be too much leakage of this helping payment from women's food crops to 
 men's cash crops? The answer comes from one Cameroonian who allows 
 his wife to fertilize her maize while he neglects to fertilize his coffee: "I 
 don't like to be hungry." 
